{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 11:53:07.721772", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nSummary\n- Overall health: Partially degraded.\n- Impacted domain: User subnet 10.1.1.0/24 (core 1, dist 1).\n- Primary issues found:\n  1) DHCP relay is down on router_dist_1_1, causing host_1_1_1_1 to lose its IP configuration and default route.\n  2) OSPF on router_core_1 is misconfigured (no networks enabled), preventing OSPF adjacency with router_dist_1_1 and thus preventing route propagation for 10.1.1.0/24 toward the rest of the network.\n- Unaffected domain: User subnet 10.2.1.0/24; end-to-end to server farm and DNS/LB services are functioning.\n\nObserved Symptoms and Tests\n- Reachability tests:\n  - host_2_1_1_1 -> load_balancer 10.200.0.7: OK (0% loss, ~2 ms RTT).\n  - host_2_1_1_1 -> dhcp_server 10.200.0.8: OK (0% loss).\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> load_balancer/dhcp_server: undetermined in bulk test; targeted tests show no routing due to missing IP.\n  - Server-farm internal reachability (dns/webs/lb/dhcp): OK.\n\n- host_1_1_1_1 interface/route state:\n  - Initially had DHCP address 10.1.1.10/24 with default via 10.1.1.1; lease was about to expire (valid_lft 7s).\n  - Shortly after, IP and routes disappeared:\n    - ip -br a shows eth0 UP with no IPv4.\n    - ip route is empty.\n    - Pings to 10.1.1.1 fail with “Network is unreachable.”\n  - Conclusion: Host lost its DHCP lease and has no connectivity on 10.1.1.0/24.\n\n- host_2_1_1_1 interface/route state:\n  - Has DHCP address 10.2.1.10/24 with default via 10.2.1.1; can reach server farm and load balancer.\n  - HTTP tests:\n    - curl http://10.200.0.3 and http://10.200.0.7 return stable timings (~1.0–1.2s total).\n    - curl http://web99.local resolves and returns similar performance.\n  - Conclusion: 10.2.1.0/24 path and DNS are healthy; OSPF routing end-to-end is intact on this side.\n\n- Switching/Access layer:\n  - switch_access_1_1_1 and switch_access_2_1_1 show Linux bridges with access/router uplinks enslaved; no obvious interface-down condition.\n\n- Router_dist_1_1 (dist for 10.1.1.0/24):\n  - L3 interfaces:\n    - br0: 10.1.1.1/24; eth1 enslaved to br0 (access-facing).\n    - eth0: 172.16.0.7/31 (core-facing).\n  - OSPF status:\n    - show ip ospf neighbor: no neighbors.\n    - show running: OSPF configured with router-id 172.16.0.7 and networks 10.1.1.0/24, 172.16.0.6/31 in area 1.\n    - OSPF Area 1 reports 0 fully adjacent neighbors.\n  - DHCP relay:\n    - systemctl status isc-dhcp-relay: inactive (dead).\n  - Routing table shows only connected networks; no learned routes to 10.200.0.0/24.\n  - Conclusion: OSPF adjacency to core is absent, and DHCP relay is not running.\n\n- Router_core_1 (core connected to router_dist_1_1):\n  - OSPF configuration:\n    - show running: only “router ospf” with router-id 172.16.0.0; no network statements.\n    - show ip ospf neighbor: no neighbors.\n  - Conclusion: OSPF is effectively not participating; no interfaces are enabled under OSPF, preventing adjacency with router_dist_1_1 and breaking routing for 10.1.1.0/24 beyond the distribution layer.\n\n- Router_dist_2_1 (dist for 10.2.1.0/24) for comparison:\n  - OSPF neighbor present and Full/Backup via 172.16.0.8/31.\n  - OSPF routes learned, including O>* 10.200.0.0/24 via core.\n  - host_2_1_1_1 uses those routes successfully to reach DNS/LB/web services.\n\nDiagnosis and Fault Localization\n- Anomaly 1: DHCP failure on subnet 10.1.1.0/24.\n  - Device: router_dist_1_1.\n  - Evidence:\n    - isc-dhcp-relay inactive (dead) on router_dist_1_1.\n    - host_1_1_1_1 lost its DHCP lease (ip address and default route disappeared; valid_lft dropped to seconds before loss).\n    - host_1_1_1_1 is unable to reach its default gateway due to lack of an IP configuration.\n  - Impact: Hosts in 10.1.1.0/24 cannot obtain/renew IP and lose all connectivity.\n\n- Anomaly 2: OSPF adjacency missing between router_dist_1_1 and core.\n  - Devices: router_core_1 (primary culprit), router_dist_1_1 (symptom).\n  - Evidence:\n    - router_core_1 OSPF has no network statements; no OSPF neighbors visible.\n    - router_dist_1_1 OSPF configured for area 1 but shows 0 neighbors on the core-facing link 172.16.0.6/31.\n    - router_dist_1_1 routing table lacks any learned routes toward 10.200.0.0/24.\n  - Impact:\n    - Even if DHCP were functional, 10.1.1.0/24 would not have L3 reachability to the server farm due to absence of OSPF routes.\n    - Core redundancy is degraded because router_core_1 is not participating in OSPF at all.\n\n- Non-issues/healthy paths confirmed:\n  - 10.2.1.0/24 domain has valid DHCP, OSPF routing to core, and end-to-end to DNS and load balancer. HTTP timings are normal.\n  - Server farm intra-reachability and services (DNS, LB) are responsive.\n\nRoot Causes\n- Root cause 1: router_core_1 OSPF misconfiguration (no “network” statements under router ospf), leading to no OSPF adjacencies with peers (including router_dist_1_1) and no route distribution for the 10.1.1.0/24 path.\n- Root cause 2: DHCP relay service down on router_dist_1_1, preventing DHCP broadcasts from 10.1.1.0/24 from being relayed to the central DHCP server, resulting in host_1_1_1_1 losing its IP configuration.\n\nCurrent Risk and Impact\n- Host(s) in 10.1.1.0/24 presently have no network connectivity due to DHCP failure and, even if restored, would still lack end-to-end reachability to server farm until OSPF adjacency with the core is fixed.\n- The rest of the network (e.g., 10.2.1.0/24 and server farm 10.200.0.0/24) appears stable.\n- Core resiliency is reduced because router_core_1 is not participating in OSPF.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 12706, "output_tokens": 5974, "total_tokens": 18680, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 12544}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 4288}}}
